steps.description:
If it's a non-linear, explore-everything game like Banjo-Kazooie or Legend of Zelda then every level should be a different theme and be very spread out. If it's a linear war game like Halo or Call of Duty make it a campaign and each level is in a predesignated order. If it's the latter it's rather easy to think up of levels so long as you have a plot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7d/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/7d/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/aid588593-v4-565px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":322,"bigWidth":"565","bigHeight":"395","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If it's the former than it's a lot trickier since you have to think up of various themes to run through with 5-10 levels. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/aid588593-v4-565px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":322,"bigWidth":"565","bigHeight":"395","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

For example if its covered in cemeteries and graveyard it's horror-themed and if it's taking place in a Himalaya-like place it's ice-themed. One of most frequently-used (and clever) themes is horror. Of course when it comes to horror make it Halloween-ish horror (the holiday) not Hellraiser-ish horror. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/83/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/8/83/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/aid588593-v4-565px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":322,"bigWidth":"565","bigHeight":"395","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

An absolute must for every non-linear game is a water-themed level. Try to introduce it early on such as Level 4 or Level 5 which is when the game should begin turning difficult. The point is to get the player more oriented to swimming (no matter how badly the controls handle) for later in the game. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/37/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/37/Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/aid588593-v4-565px-Make-a-Video-Game-Level-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":322,"bigWidth":"565","bigHeight":"395","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
